The death of a girl who choked to death in a supermarket has been ruled a ‘tragic accident’. Three-year-old Poppy Reardon was at Asda with her dad, Conor, in Aintree, Liverpool, preparing for a camping trip the next day. While he carried her she started chewing on the plastic toggle on his hoodie when a piece came off. She started choking and off-duty paramedic David Fitzmurphy, who was shopping  at the time, tried to intervene. His partner alerted him to Poppy who had was going blue in one of the aisles after her parents, Rhian and Conor, became ‘really distressed’. He started mouth-to-mouth but said it ‘felt like [the air] wasn’t going in. Another off-duty healthcare worker came to perform CPR until an ambulance crew arrived, by which time she was already in cardiac arrest. Poppy was taken to Alder Hey Children’s Hospital but she could not breathe on her own and there were no signs of life despite CPR and adremaline shots. After hearing there had been no similar incidents of this nature with the top Conor was wearing, coroner Julie Goulding gave a verdict of accidental death. She sent her ‘deepest condolences to the young family and friends for their very tragic and sad loss.’ Get in touch with our news team by emailing us at webnews@metro.co.uk. For more stories like this, check our news page.